Representative from SC-01 (1995-2001, 2013–2019) Governor of South Carolina (2003–2011) South Carolina September 8, 2019 November 12, 2019 Campaign FEC filing[65] 4,258 (0.03%) 0 [35][36] The following notable individuals who did not meet the criteria to become a major candidate have suspended their campaigns: Augustus Sol Invictus, attorney, white nationalist, and far-right activist[66][67][68] Zoltan Istvan, transhumanist activist[69][70] Declined to be candidates[edit] The individuals in this section have been the subject of 2020 presidential speculation but have publicly said they will not seek the presidency in 2020. Endorsed Trump[edit] Greg Abbott, Governor of Texas[71][72][73] Steve Bannon, former Trump campaign manager and White House Chief Strategist[74][75][76] Chris Christie, former governor of New Jersey; 2016 presidential candidate[77][78][79] Ted Cruz, U.S. senator from Texas; 2016 presidential candidate[80][81][82] Nikki Haley, former ambassador to the United Nations; former governor of South Carolina[83][84][85] Rand Paul, U.S. senator from Kentucky; 2016 presidential candidate[86][87][88] Mike Pence, Vice President of the United States; former governor of Indiana[89][90][91] Marco Rubio, U.S. senator from Florida; 2016 presidential candidate[92][93] Scott Walker, former governor of Wisconsin; 2016 presidential candidate[94][95] Others[edit] Charlie Baker, Governor of Massachusetts[96] Jeb Bush, former governor of Florida; 2016 presidential candidate[97][98] Bob Corker, former U.S. senator from Tennessee[99] Tom Cotton, U.S. senator from Arkansas[100][101] (running for re-election)[102] Ann Coulter, conservative columnist[103] Mark Cuban, owner of Dallas Mavericks from Texas[104][105] Carly Fiorina, business executive and 2016 presidential candidate[106][107] Jeff Flake, former U.S. senator from Arizona; former U.S. representative[108] Larry Hogan, Governor of Maryland[109][110] Jon Huntsman Jr., Ambassador to Russia; former governor of Utah[111][112](running for Governor)[113] John Kasich, former governor of Ohio; former U.S. representative; candidate for President in 2000 and in 2016[114][115] James Mattis, former secretary of defense[116][117] Austin Petersen, 2016 Libertarian candidate for president[118] Mitt Romney, U.S. senator from Utah; 2012 presidential nominee; former governor of Massachusetts[119][120] Meg Whitman, business executive; nominee for governor of California in 2010[121][122] Debates[edit] Main article: 2020 Republican Party presidential debates The Republican National Committee (RNC) has made no plans to host any official primary debates. On May 3, 2018, the party voted to eliminate their debate committee, which, according to CNN, served as "a warning to would-be Republican rivals of President Donald Trump about his strong support among party loyalists".[123] Trump has declined any interest in participating in any primary debates, saying he was "not looking to give [opponents] any credibility".[124] Debates among the challengers have been scheduled without the RNC's involvement. Business Insider hosted a debate on September 24 featuring two of Trump's primary challengers. It took place at the news outlet's headquarters in New York City, and was hosted by Business Insider's CEO Henry Blodgett, politics editor Anthony Fisher, and columnist Linette Lopez.[125] Walsh and Weld agreed to attend, but Sanford had a scheduling conflict and eventually declined.[126][127] An invitation was also sent to the president, but he also declined.[127] Politicon held a debate between Sanford, Walsh, and Weld on October 26 at its 2019 convention in Nashville, Tennessee[128] and Forbes also held a debate between the three on October 28 at its Under 30 Summit in Detroit, Michigan.[129] Both Walsh and Weld took part in a few forums that also featured Democratic candidates.[130][131][132] Cancelation of state caucuses or primaries[edit] The Washington Examiner reported on December 19, 2018, that the South Carolina Republican Party had not ruled out forgoing a primary contest to protect Trump from any primary challengers. Party chairman Drew McKissick stated, "Considering the fact that the entire party supports the president, we'll end up doing what's in the president's best interest."[133] On January 24, another Washington Examiner report indicated that the Kansas Republican Party was "likely" to scrap its presidential caucus to "save resources".[134] In August 2019, the Associated Press reported that the Nevada Republican Party was also contemplating canceling their caucuses, with the state party spokesman, Keith Schipper, saying it "isn't about any kind of conspiracy theory about protecting the president ... He's going to be the nominee ... This is about protecting resources to make sure that the president wins in Nevada and that Republicans up and down the ballot win in 2020."[135] On September 6, both of Trump's main challengers at the time, Bill Weld and Joe Walsh, criticized these cancellations as undemocratic.[136] The Trump campaign and GOP officials cited the fact that Republicans canceled several state primaries when George H.W. Bush and George W. Bush sought a second term in 1992 and 2004, respectively; and Democrats scrapped some of their primaries when Bill Clinton and Barack Obama were seeking reelection in 1996 and 2012, respectively.[137][138] Weld and Walsh were joined by Mark Sanford in a joint op-ed in The Washington Post on September 13, 2019 which criticized the party for cancelling those primaries.[139] Kansas,[140] Nevada and South Carolina's state committees officially voted on September 7, 2019, to cancel their caucus and primary.[7] The Arizona state Republican Party indicated two days later that it will not hold a primary.[141] These four were joined by the Alaska state Republican party on September 21, when its central committee announced they would not hold a presidential primary.[142] Virginia Republicans decided to allocate delegates at the state convention.[143] The Nevada State committee chairman said the committee would meet on February 23, 2020 and bind their delegates to Trump.[144] The Hawaii GOP voted to cancel its primary and bind its 19 delegates to Trump on December 11.[145] The New York GOP on March 3 decided to cancel its primary after neither De La Fuente, Weld, nor Walsh submitted the required number of names of their delegates in order to qualify for their ballot.[146] The delegate candidates bound to the president were thus automatically elected. Other states were instead encouraged to use "winner-takes-all" systems to award delegates instead of using proportional allocation "to avoid dissent" at the convention.[8] Timeline[edit] Overview[edit] Active campaign Exploratory committee Withdrawn candidate Midterm elections Iowa caucuses Super Tuesday Republican convention 2017–18[edit] Incumbent President Donald Trump speaking at his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, on February 18, 2017 February 18, 2017: Donald Trump informally announces his candidacy for a second term and holds the first of a series of occasional reelection campaign rallies in Melbourne, Florida, only one month after assuming office.[147] June 23, 2018: Trump delivers remarks at the Nevada Republican Convention in Las Vegas.[148] July 18, 2018: Charlotte, North Carolina is chosen as the site for the 2020 Republican National Convention.[149] November 7, 2018: Trump confirms that Mike Pence will remain his vice presidential pick.[150] 2019[edit] Former Gov. Bill Weld announcing the formation of his exploratory committee on February 15, 2019. He launched his campaign two months later. Former Rep. Joe Walsh announced his campaign on August 25, 2019. He withdrew after finishing Iowa with 1%. Former Rep. Mark Sanford announced his campaign on September 8, 2019. He withdrew from the race two months later. January 17: Former Massachusetts governor Bill Weld changes his voter registration from Libertarian back to Republican, furthering speculation he will announce a primary challenge against Trump.[151] January 23: The Republican National Committee votes unanimously to express "undivided support" of Trump's "effective presidency".[5] February 11: Trump holds his first mass rally since assuming the presidency in El Paso, Texas, with Brad Parscale, John Cornyn, Lance Berkman, Ted Cruz and Donald Trump Jr.[152] February 15: Weld announces the formation of an exploratory committee, becoming the president's first official notable challenger.[153] April 15: Weld officially announces his candidacy.[154] May 16: Businessman and perennial candidate Rocky De La Fuente files to run.[155] June 1: Speculative challenger Maryland governor Larry Hogan announces that he will not run against Trump in the primary.[156] June 18: Trump formally launches his 2020 re-election campaign at a rally in Orlando, Florida, with Donald Trump Jr., Mike Pence, Melania Trump, Karen Pence, Lara Trump, and Sarah Sanders.[157] July 30: Intending to force Trump to reveal his taxes, Democratic California governor Gavin Newsom signs a bill into state law requiring that presidential candidates release the last five years of their tax returns in order to qualify for the California primary ballot. Republican presidential candidate Rocky De La Fuente files suit directly challenging the constitutionality of the law.[158][159] August 5–6: Additional lawsuits are filed by the Trump campaign, the Republican National Committee, the California Republican Party, and the conservative activist group Judicial Watch to challenge the California law requiring candidates to release their tax returns.[160][161] August 25: Former Illinois congressman Joe Walsh officially announces his candidacy, becoming the president's second official notable challenger.[162] September 7: Three state committees vote to cancel their respective primaries/caucuses: Kansas,[140] Nevada, and South Carolina.[7] September 8: Former South Carolina governor and congressman Mark Sanford officially announces his candidacy, becoming the president's third notable challenger.[35] As the California law requiring candidates to disclose their tax returns works its way through the courts, the California Republican Party modifies its delegate selection rules as a stop-gap measure, changing its primary from a binding to a non-binding one with a party state convention selecting its national convention delegates directly.[163] September 9: The Arizona Republican Party officially notifies Arizona secretary of state Katie Hobbs that they will forego the Arizona Republican primary.[141] September 21: The Alaska Republican Party cancels its primary.[164] September 23: Donald Trump qualifies for the Vermont primary.[165] September 24: Business Insider hosted a debate between Weld and Walsh.[125] October 1: Deadline for state parties to file delegate selection plans with the Republican National Committee.[166] October 26: Politicon debate between the main challengers.[128] October 28: Forbes debate between the main challengers.[129] October 31: Minnesota committee submits only Trump's name for the primary ballot.[167][168] November 8: Filing deadline to appear on the Alabama Republican primary ballot. Mark Sanford and Joe Walsh failed to appear, while Donald Trump and Bill Weld both qualified.[169] November 12: Mark Sanford dropped out of the race.[36] Filing deadline to appear on the Arkansas Republican primary ballot. Mark Sanford (who dropped out the day of the deadline) and Joe Walsh fail to appear, while Rocky De La Fuente, Donald Trump, and Bill Weld qualify.[170] November 15: Filing deadline to appear on the New Hampshire Republican primary ballot. Rocky De La Fuente, Donald Trump, Bill Weld, and Joe Walsh all qualify.[171] November 21: The California Supreme Court declares that the state law requiring primary candidates to disclose their tax returns violates the state constitution and cannot be enforced.[172] November 26: Rocky De La Fuente filed a lawsuit against the state of Minnesota alleging that its ballot access law for presidential primaries is unconstitutional. Minnesota had previously barred all other candidates from its Republican presidential primary other than Donald Trump on October 31.[173] December 6: The California Secretary of State released the list of "Generally Recognized Presidential Candidates" for the upcoming March 3, 2020 election, including seven Republicans.[174] December 11: The Hawaii Republican state committee cancels the caucuses and appoints 19 national convention delegates and binds them to Trump, who receives his first official victory.[145] A state court affirms the South Carolina's GOP's right to cancel its primary.[175] December 18: The House of Representatives formally votes almost along party lines to impeach Trump.[176] December 20: North Carolina announces that Walsh and Weld will appear on the ballot for their GOP primaries.[177] Jim Martin, a business-operator from Lake Elmo, Minnesota, joins with Rocky De La Fuente in suing the state in supreme court for empowering the Republican Party of Minnesota to only print Trump's name on primary ballots.[178] 2020[edit] January[edit] January 9: Trump holds his first "Keep America Great" Rally of the year at the Huntington Center in Toledo, Ohio.[179] January 17: Early voting begins in Minnesota.[180] January 18: First of a series of district conventions in North Dakota, which elect delegates to the state convention. The North Dakota Republican Party does not hold any presidential preference caucus or primary per se, but instead selects their national convention delegates directly at the state party convention.[181][182] January 30: Trump holds a rally in Des Moines, Iowa, the largest event of the caucus campaign.[183] January 31: The Kansas Republican convention assembles, where the second delegation to the national convention is chosen and officially bound to Trump.[184][185][140][186] February[edit] February 3: Trump wins the Iowa caucuses, receiving 97% of the votes cast. Weld earns one delegate.[187] February 4: Trump gives his final State of the Union address of this term.[188] February 5: The United States Senate acquits Trump.[189] February 7: Joe Walsh dropped out of the race.[190] February 10: Trump holds a rally in Manchester, New Hampshire.[191] February 11: Trump wins the New Hampshire primary with 86% of the vote.[192] February 21: Trump holds a rally in Las Vegas prior to the Nevada state committee's "presidential preference poll."[193] February 22: The Nevada state committee binds the state delegation to Trump.[194] March[edit] March 3: Trump wins all 13 Super Tuesday primaries: Alabama, Arkansas, California, Colorado, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, North Carolina, Oklahoma, Tennessee, Texas, Utah, and Vermont.[195] New York cancels its Republican primary after Trump is the only candidate to submit the required number of names of his delegates.[146] The candidates for delegate are declared elected.[196] March 10: Trump wins all 6 races held on this date: Idaho,[197] Michigan, Mississippi, and Missouri;[198] as well as Washington (where he was the only candidate on the ballot),[199] and North Dakota (a non-binding firehouse caucus where he was also unopposed).[200] March 14: All nine delegates in the Guam convention are pledged to Donald Trump.[201] March 15: Trump wins all nine delegates in the Northern Mariana Islands Republican caucuses.[202] March 17: With wins in Florida and Illinois giving him a majority of delegates, President Donald Trump becomes the presumptive Republican presidential nominee.[203] March 18: Bill Weld dropped out of the race.[204] March 19: Connecticut rescheduled its primary from April 28 to June 2.[205] March 20: Indiana rescheduled its expected state primary of May 5 to June 2. [206] April[edit] April 8: New Jersey rescheduled its primary election from June 2 to July 7.[207] April 13: Trump won the 2020 Wisconsin Republican primary unopposed.[208] April 14: Louisiana rescheduled its primary for the second time, moving the date from June 20 to July 11.[209] April 17: Connecticut rescheduled its primary for a second time, from June 2 to August 11.[210] April 28: Trump won the 2020 Ohio Republican primary unopposed.[citation needed] Primary and caucus calendar[edit] Some later primary and caucus dates may change depending on legislation passed before the scheduled primary dates.[211] States designated with a "†" indicate that Trump is running unopposed. Date Total pledged delegates[212] Primaries/caucuses February 3 40 Iowa caucuses[213] February 11 22 New Hampshire primary[211] February 22 25 Nevada state convention March 3 (Super Tuesday) 785 50 40 172 37 22 41 39 71 43 58 155 40 17 Alabama primary Arkansas primary California primary Colorado primary Maine primary† Massachusetts primary Minnesota primary† North Carolina primary Oklahoma primary Tennessee primary Texas primary Utah primary Vermont primary[211] March 10 242 32 73 40 54 43 Idaho primary Michigan primary Mississippi primary Missouri primary Washington primary†[211] see convention below End of North Dakota caucuses†[200][214] March 14 9[215] Guam convention[211] March 15 9[216] Northern Mariana Islands caucus[211] March 17 189 122 67 Florida primary Illinois primary March 18 9[217] American Samoa caucus[211] TBD[218] 29 North Dakota state convention[219] April 2–4 29 Alaska state convention April 4 – May 30 9[220] Virgin Islands caucuses[211] April 7 52 Wisconsin primary†[221] April 9 see convention below End of Arizona caucuses†[222] April 17 see convention below End of Virginia caucuses†[223] April 28 82 Ohio primary†[211] May 1–2 98 48 50 Virginia state convention†[223] South Carolina state convention May 9 86 57 29[224] Arizona state convention†[225] Wyoming state convention[211] May 12 36 Nebraska primary[211] May 19 28 Oregon primary[211] June 2 316 16 58 38 27 22 88 19 29 19[226] Delaware primary Indiana primary Maryland p