ballot but withdrew from the primary, color indicating if the candidate’s name appeared on the ballot (red for not on the ballot, green for on the ballot). States that have not yet announced any candidates who are on the ballot are not included. State Date Rocky De La Fuente (21)[j] Donald Trump (35) Joe Walsh (14) Bill Weld (25) Other (12) Ref. Iowa February 3 No Yes Yes Yes No [241] New Hampshire February 11 Yes Yes Yes Yes Yes[k] [171] Alabama March 3 W[l] Yes No Yes No [242] Arkansas March 3 W[m] Yes No Yes No [243] California March 3 Yes Yes Yes Yes Yes[n] [244] Colorado March 3 W[l] Yes Yes Yes Yes[n] [245] Maine March 3 No Yes No No No [246] Massachusetts March 3 Yes Yes Yes Yes No [247][248] Minnesota March 3 No Yes No No No [249] North Carolina March 3 No Yes Yes Yes No [250] Oklahoma March 3 Yes Yes Yes No Yes[o] [251] Tennessee March 3 No Yes Yes Yes No [252] Texas March 3 Yes Yes Yes Yes Yes[o] [253] Utah March 3 W[m] Yes Yes Yes Yes[p] [254] Vermont March 3 Yes Yes No Yes No [165] Idaho March 10 Yes Yes Yes Yes Yes[q] [255] Michigan March 10 No Yes Yes Yes Yes[r] [256] Mississippi March 10 Yes Yes No Yes No [257] Missouri March 10 W[l] Yes Yes Yes Yes[q] [258] Washington March 10 No Yes No No No [259] Florida March 17 Yes Yes Yes Yes No [260] Illinois March 17 Yes Yes No No No [261] Wisconsin April 7 No Yes No No No [262] Ohio April 28 No Yes No No No [263] Nebraska May 12 No Yes No Yes No [264] Delaware June 2 Yes Yes No No No [265] Indiana June 2 No Yes No Yes No [266] Maryland June 2 No Yes No Yes No [267] New Mexico June 2 No Yes No No No [268] Pennsylvania June 2 Yes Yes No Yes No [269] Rhode Island June 2 Yes Yes No Yes Yes[s] [270] Georgia June 9 No Yes No No No [271] West Virginia June 9 Yes Yes No Yes Yes[q] [272] New Jersey July 7 No Yes No No Yes[q] [273] Louisiana July 11 Yes Yes No Yes Yes[q] [274] Connecticut August 11 Yes Yes No W No [275] National convention[edit] Main article: 2020 Republican National Convention Bids for the Republican National Convention were solicited in the fall of 2017, with finalists being announced early the following spring. On July 18, 2018, Charlotte, North Carolina's Spectrum Center was chosen as the site of the convention.[149] Endorsements[edit] This is a list of endorsements for declared candidates for the Republican primaries for the 2020 United States presidential election. Donald Trump[edit] Main article: List of Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign endorsements See also: Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign Withdrawn candidates[edit] Joe Walsh[edit] See also: Joe Walsh 2020 presidential campaign List of Joe Walsh endorsements Individuals George Conway, attorney and spouse of Kellyanne Conway[276] Bill Weld[edit] See also: Bill Weld 2020 presidential campaign List of Bill Weld endorsements U.S. Executive Branch officials Betty Tamposi, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State for Consular Affairs (1989-1992)[277] Trevor Potter, Commissioner of the Federal Election Commission (1991-1995)[278] U.S. Representatives William F. Clinger Jr., U.S. Representative from PA-23 1979-1993, and PA-05 (1993-1997)[279] Steven T. Kuykendall, U.S. Representative from CA-36 (1999-2001)[279] Jim Leach, U.S. Representative from IA-01 (1977-2003), and IA-02 (2003-2007)[280] Tom Petri, U.S. Representative from WI-06 (1979-2015)[279] Dick Zimmer, U.S. Representative from NJ-12 (1991-1997)[279] Governors Gary Johnson, Governor of New Mexico (1995-2003) and Libertarian nominee for President in 2016 (co-endorsement with Tulsi Gabbard)[279] Phil Scott, Governor of Vermont (2017-present)[281] Christine Todd Whitman, Governor of New Jersey (1994-2001) and Administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency (2001-2003)[279] Statewide officials Robert Durand, Massachusetts Secretary of Environmental Affairs (1999-2003)[282] State legislators Doug Scamman, State Representative from New Hampshire (Rockingham District 13) (2004-2010)[279] Stella Scamman, State Representative from New Hampshire (Rock